Catalog of selector and locator patterns that cause flakes, brittle tests, or false passes. Every entry has the same shape: **pattern**, **failure mode**, **replacement**.

---

## Starter entries (ported from Progressive CIT)

### 1. `nth-child` / `nth-of-type` / `eq(n)`

```ts
// ❌ breaks on any sibling reorder
page.locator('tbody tr:nth-child(3) td:nth-child(2) button');
```

**Failure mode:** a UX pass that adds a "status" column, or a data change that reorders rows, silently moves the target element. Tests pass against stale positions for weeks before someone notices.

**Replacement:** `data-testid` on the row + column, resolved via `getByRole('row', { name }).getByTestId('status-cell')`.

---

### 2. Styling-class selectors

```ts
// ❌ `.btn-primary` is a Bootstrap utility — it'll change when the design
//    system updates, and the test will silently pass against the wrong element.
page.locator('button.btn-primary');
```

**Failure mode:** Theme upgrade renames `.btn-primary` to `.btn-filled`; the selector matches nothing; the test passes because the assertion also couldn't find what it was looking for.

**Replacement:** `page.getByTestId('submit-claim-button')`.

---

### 3. XPath locators

```ts
// ❌ illegible, brittle, Playwright has better APIs for every case
page.locator('xpath=//div[contains(@class, "card")]//button[text()="Save"]');
```

**Failure mode:** New wrapper `<div>` inserted anywhere in the ancestor chain breaks the path. The error message ("locator not found") gives no hint where in the chain the break happened.

**Replacement:** `getByRole('button', { name: 'Save' })` or `getByTestId('save-card-button')`.

---

### 4. `waitForTimeout` as a wait primitive

```ts
// ❌ race — sometimes the modal animates in faster or slower than 500ms
await page.click('[data-testid="open-modal"]');
await page.waitForTimeout(500);
await page.click('[data-testid="modal-confirm"]');
```

**Failure mode:** CI runs are slower than local dev; the 500ms passes before the modal finishes animating; the click lands on the underlay. Flake rate goes up with CI load.

**Replacement:** `waitForStable()` from `helpers.ts`, or deterministic `.waitFor({ state: 'visible' })` on the target locator.

---

### 5. Internationalizable text locators on controls

```ts
// ❌ the moment i18n lands, French users break the test suite
page.getByText('Submit');
```

**Failure mode:** Adding a locale silently changes the rendered text; the test fails with no connection back to the i18n work. Triage wastes hours.

**Replacement:** `page.getByTestId('submit-claim-button')` for interactive elements; `page.getByRole('button', { name: /submit/i })` when i18n isn't yet planned and you want a regex fallback.

---

### 6. Generated / hash-based IDs

```ts
// ❌ Next.js and similar bundlers generate these on build
page.locator('#__next-route-0_123');
```

**Failure mode:** Framework upgrade regenerates the hash scheme; every test using these IDs fails simultaneously.

**Replacement:** `data-testid` on the meaningful element, or `getByRole` on the semantic wrapper.

---

### 7. Inline locator in spec (page-object boundary violation)

```ts
// ❌ spec reaches into the DOM directly
test('submits claim', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.getByTestId('submit-claim-button').click();
});
```

**Failure mode:** When the feature is refactored and the testid renames (`submit-claim` → `file-claim`), every spec needs to change individually. Locator drift spreads across N spec files instead of being contained in one page object.

**Replacement:** move locator into a page object; spec calls `claimsPage.submit()`. See `shared/locator-hierarchy.md`.

---

## How to add a new entry

1. **Record the flake**: paste the failing selector + the failure message.
2. **Diagnose the root cause**: what changed that broke it? (reorder, theme, i18n, framework upgrade, timing)
3. **Write the entry**: pattern / failure mode / replacement — same shape as above.
4. **Link from the offending PR**: in the fix PR, cite `docs/testing/anti-patterns.md#your-new-entry` in the description so future contributors find it.
5. **Evaluator reads this file**: Pass 1 review will block PRs that introduce patterns already cataloged here.

---

## Catalog review cadence

- **Weekly** (Tier-Standard/Full): scan new entries for duplicates; merge if two entries describe the same failure mode.
- **Per release** (all tiers): confirm every entry still reflects current framework behavior — frameworks fix bugs, and an entry may be obsolete.
- **On flake**: add a new entry before merging the fix. No catalog entry, no merge.
